esh manual chapter 10 laser safety skip to main content slac web people slac home slac today for staff for users directorates ets operations lcls particle physics & astrophysics photon science ssrl es & h esh web manual esh home hazardous activities laser esh manual chapter 10 laser safety the purpose of this program is to mitigate the hazards posed by optical lasers which operate at wavelengths between 180 nanometer and 1 millimeter high power lasers class 3b and class 4 are used at slac in research and accelerator operations the primary hazard associated with their operation is potential eye damage other potential hazards include skin burns electrical currents explosions fires toxic material laser generated air contaminants collateral radiation noise and ultraviolet light low power lasers class 2 and class 3r include laser pointers and alignment lasers they are safe when used as intended but require some controls quick start summary pdf full chapter pdf procedures and requirements laser safety general requirements pdf class 2 and class 3r laser operation requirements pdf laser pointer requirements pdf class 3b and class 4 laser operation requirements pdf laser controlled area requirements pdf class 3b and class 4 laser cohe requirements pdf core laser safety practices requirements pdf class 3b and class 4 laser eyewear protection requirements pdf laser controlled area visitor requirements pdf student requirements pdf laser service subcontractor work planning and control procedure pdf forms and tools qualified laser operator approval form pdf system laser safety officer approval form pdf approval to operate form pdf slac internal page laser safety sharepoint site program ownership department radiation protection contact program manager mike woods additional contacts mike woods laser safety officer alan fry chair laser safety committee laser safety committee icon for secured site link membership list icon for secured site link your browser does not have the ability 